33718/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Taking counterterrorism legislation and policy as its focal point, this project makes an original contribution to the way that law, politics and their interrelation are theorised. Its key aim is to show how post-9/11 US counterterrorism legislation has important effects on the overall polity ? ie the structure of the state; its practices, modalities and logic; the orientation and objectives of state power; and the relations between the state and society. In doing so, and following from the conceptualisation of the state as a social relation, the project develops an understanding of law as a particular codification of social relations and dynamics, mediated by legal structures, logics, personnel, and traditions. This framework avoids the dangers of self-referential analysis and of the automatic application of the findings of legal analysis to the state and politics ? tendencies that characterise much of the analysis of counterterrorism legislation. By traversing state-theory and sociolegal studies, the project aims to develop a novel framework for theorising the relationship between law and the state ? the relative locations, mutual determinations, implications, and tensions characterising these two, distinct but interconnected, mediated expressions of social relations ? building a bridgehead between two fields that rarely engage with each other in meaningful, non-schematic ways. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>56848</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOut